data.content:
## Thread.Abort Migration to .NET 8

### What breaks and why

In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — it simply doesn't work. `ThreadAbortException` is never raised, and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is obsolete (`SYSLIB0006`). You must switch to **cooperative cancellation**.

### Pattern classification

Your code contains three interrelated patterns:

| Location | Pattern | Issue |
|---|---|---|
| `Stop()` → `_workerThread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `PlatformNotSupportedException` at runtime |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control-flow cleanup | Never caught — `ThreadAbortException` is never thrown |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Obsolete (`SYSLIB0006`) |

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — same logic that was in the
                // ThreadAbortException catch block
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop gracefully
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait up to 2 seconds for the thread to finish
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't stop in time — log a warning.
            // There is NO .NET 8 equivalent of Thread.Abort().
            // If GetNextItem/ProcessItem can't observe the token,
            // the thread will only stop when the process exits
            // (IsBackground = true ensures this).
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key changes explained

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationTokenSource` + `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs (`WaitHandle`, async I/O) that a plain `bool` cannot interrupt |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative signal; no `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | The `when` filter avoids catching unrelated `OperationCanceledException`s from other sources |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed | Not needed — `OperationCanceledException` doesn't auto-rethrow like `ThreadAbortException` did |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` | `_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2))` | Actually waits for the thread instead of sleeping blindly |

### Critical pitfall: `GetNextItem` must cooperate

The biggest risk is that `GetNextItem()` **blocks** (e.g., on a queue or socket). If it doesn't observe the token, cancellation stalls until it unblocks on its own. You must thread the token through:

```csharp
// ❌ Before — blocks indefinitely, ignores cancellation
private WorkItem GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // BlockingCollection.Take()
}

// ✅ After — wakes up immediately on cancel
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

If `GetNextItem` calls a synchronous API that **doesn't** accept a token (e.g., a raw `socket.Receive()`), replace it with an async overload or use `token.WaitHandle` to race against it. As a last resort, if the code truly cannot cooperate, move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()` — that's the only .NET 8 equivalent of a forcible stop.

### Validation checklist

- ✅ No `Thread.Abort`, `ThreadAbortException`, or `Thread.ResetAbort` references remain
- ✅ No `SYSLIB0006` warnings
- ✅ `CancellationTokenSource` is disposed via `IDisposable`
- ✅ Token is passed through the full call chain (`GetNextItem(token)`)
- ✅ `finally` block (`FlushBuffers`) still executes on both normal exit and cancellation
